Surface Air Temperature

Introduction

This webpage is showing the surface air temperature for piControl (present day), and 4 times the CO2 level, which represents the future. The libraries used in the first part of the code below are what store all of the functions that will be used later in the page. Below the libraries is the data used for the presesnt day surface air temperatue for the world.

library(ggplot2)
library(ncdf4)
library(zoo)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(raster)
library(rasterVis)
library(sf)
library(ncdf.tools)
library(rgdal)
nc_path <- "/Users/jacobmaurer/Documents/College/Geography490/Projects/geog490//"
nc_name <- "PMIP3_tas_piControl_ltm_gcm_CMIP5_CCSM4_OA.nc"
nc_file <- paste(nc_path, nc_name, sep="")
tas_piControl <- raster(nc_file, varname = "tas_ltm")
tas_piControl <- rotate(tas_piControl)
shp_path <- "/Users/jacobmaurer/Documents/College/Geography490/Projects/geog490//"

Like above, this code is similar, but it’s calling a different file. This chunk of code is calling the 4 x CO2 surface air temperature file.

nc_path <- "/Users/jacobmaurer/Documents/College/Geography490/Projects/geog490//"

Country Outlines

In order to map surface air temperature, you need to show the actual locations, so a country outline map was created in order to shows all of the countries in the world. This was created by adding a world shapefile, seting the geometry of the projection, adding a color, then adding a title.

shp_path <- "/Users/jacobmaurer/Documents/College/Geography490/Projects/geog490//"
shp_name <- "ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp"
shp_file <- paste(shp_path, shp_name, sep="")
world_shp <- read_sf(shp_file)
world_outline <- as(st_geometry(world_shp), Class="Spatial")
plot(world_outline, col="gray80", lwd=1, main = "Country Outline")

Coastal Outline

While having every coutry can be useful, a coastal outline map was created to allow for plots that look more pleasing. This allows for the plots to be shown without a lot of lines in smaller countries such as Europe. With the coastal outline, it is easy to fill in the area with color to get a better represesntation of the actual surface air temperature.

coast_shp_path <- "/Users/jacobmaurer/Documents/College/Geography490/Projects/geog490//"
coast_shp_name <- "ne_10m_coastline.shp"
coast_shp_file <- paste(coast_shp_path, coast_shp_name, sep="")
# read the shapefile
coast_shp <- read_sf(coast_shp_file)
coast_outline <- as(st_geometry(coast_shp), Class="Spatial")
# plot the outline
plot(coast_outline, col="gray50", lwd=1, main = "Coastal Outline")

Present Day Surface Air Temperature

Centered on Africa, this map below shows the piControl surface air temperature. pi stands for pre-industrial, but the levels being showsn are considered current day. The pi readings were taken in 1850 when the conditions were 280 ppm, current day is around 410 ppm. The blue is a decrese in temperature and the red is an increase. As you expect, the equator is hot and the poles are cold.

mapTheme <- rasterTheme(region=rev(brewer.pal(8,"RdBu")))
plt <- levelplot(tas_piControl, margin=F, par.settings=mapTheme, main = "piControl SAT")
plt + latticeExtra::layer(sp.lines(world_outline, col="gray30", lwd=0.5))

4 x CO2 Surface Air Temperature

Similar to the map above, this map shows the surface air temperatre for the world at 4 times the pre-industrial days (4xCO2). As you can see, the blue is diminishing and the red is spreading, as climatologists expect in the future. The increase in temperature caused the scale on the right to go up 10 more degrees in order to plot the data.

mapTheme <- rasterTheme(region=rev(brewer.pal(8,"RdBu")))
plt <- levelplot(tas_4xC02, margin=F, par.settings=mapTheme, main = "4xCO2 SAT")
plt + latticeExtra::layer(sp.lines(world_outline, col="gray30", lwd=0.5))

Monthly plot of 4 x C02 SAT

This is a monthly plot of the 4 x C02 level to compare temperature throughout the year. As with the comparison of the whole year map, these are warmer and have less blue occuring on the map. This map shows a good representation of where the surface air temperature will be affecting first, and from the plots below, you can see an increase in temperature around the Indian Ocean and a small chunk of the Eastern Pacific Ocean. You can also see areas in the South Pole that were white (ice), but are now turning into blue with an increased temperture.This will allow for scientists to see areas that will be affected and allow for them to focus on certain regions.

Difference Map

This is the difference between the 4x C02 and the present day monthly maps. As expected, the world is hotter, but there’s a chunk of the mid-Atlantic Ocean that has a hole. This hole is a hole in the ozone layer that is cooler than everywhere else due to no ozone being present. This ozone depletion has been occuring since the 1970’s, and consists of “a steady lowering of about four percent in the total amount of ozone in Earth’s atmosphere, and a much larger springtime decrease in stratospheric ozone around Earth’s polar regions.” Being able to map these features allows for scientists to watch how the ozone hole is changin over time, and weather it’s increaseing or decreasing.

monthly_diff <- monthly_4xC02 - monthly_piControl
pngfile <- "monthly_diff.png"
png(pngfile, width=729, height=729) # open the file
cutpts <- c(-10,-5,-2,-1,-0.5,0,0.5,1,2,5,10)
plt <- levelplot(monthly_diff, main = "Monthly Difference Maps", at=cutpts, cuts=11, pretty=T, 
                 col.regions=rev((brewer.pal(10,"RdBu"))))
plt + latticeExtra::layer(sp.lines(coast_outline, col="black", lwd=0.5))
dev.off()
